fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Suppose \vec {0}' is another zero vector. Then
\vec {0}'=\vec {0}'+\vec {0}=\vec {0}+\vec {0}'=\vec {0}
hence \vec {0}=\vec {0}'.

We see
v+(-1)v=1v+(-1)v=(1+(-1))v=0v=\vec {0}
by Scalar multiples of zero vector are the zero vector.

Let b_{1},b_{2}\in  A be inverses for a. Then
\begin {align} b_{1}&=\mu (b_{1},e)\\ &=\mu (b_{1},\mu (a,b_{2}))\\ &=\mu (\mu (b_{1},a),b_{2})\hbox { by associativity}\\ &=\mu (e,b_{2})\\ &=b_{2}.\end {align}
Hence the result.
